As regards the outward bound vessels, the thirty-one leaving in 1433 were laden by about a hundred merchants‚ of whom one-third were English3 in 1472 the number of the laders of the twenty-three outgoing vessels was reduced by about one half, the proportion of English remaining the same—one third.¹

This reduction in the number, both of ships and laders, with no correspondingly large seduction in the amount of trade, suggests not only an increase in the size of the ships, but also that capital was becoming concentrated in a few hands. The fact that the reduction in the proportion of Englishmen sharing in the cargoes was greater among the importers than the exporters further suggests that this rapid growth of great capitalists had taken place rather in Italy than in England; with the result that only a feW, comparatively speaking, of the richest of the Southampton merchants could compete with the foreigners and maintain their places as sharers in the import trade. The natural facilities for export possessed by the natives of a country probably accounts for their having better maintained their position in this branch of trade.

Incidentally, the view that Southampton men were hard pressed by foreign competition in the third quarter of the fifteenth century receives some confirmation from the obvious hostility to aliens which appears at the end of the reign of Henry VI and the beginning of that of Edward IV. The Chancery Rolls at this period are full of complaints by aliens who had been unjustly treated in the Southampton court, and in this matter there seems to have been little to choose between the oligarchic and the popular parties.

If the foreign competition, however, resulted, as it seems to have done, in the concentration of capital in a few hands, then it must certainly have tended to oligarchy. If the development of trade favoured the large capitalist, then tlie concentration of political would probably follow that of economic power.
